With ongoing developments in the field of metabolic disorders and antiviral therapy, and the ability to offer liver transplantation to small babies, an overall survival of 40% has been achieved. Early recognition of liver failure, good supportive care and prompt referral to a paediatric liver transplant centre are essential elements in improving the outcome for these babies. Decisions about contra-indications to and timing of transplantation are complex as many of the disease processes are still evolving in the neonatal period, and extrahepatic disease, which cannot be corrected by a transplant, may appear later.", "references": ["53e9ae97b7602d97038bbe7f", "53e9bb7ab7602d97047bad2a", "53e9a885b7602d97031d4600", "56d83ae0dabfae2eee5e7200", "56d8b69ddabfae2eee0d4f97", "53e9b627b7602d970417f553", "55a491f2612ca648689b7ca0", "55a3f6412401c6de3b7bf3f6", "53e9b6a2b7602d970421d7de", "53e99837b7602d970205e15d", "53e9a1f3b7602d9702af8578", "53e9ac42b7602d970360e1ff", "53e9a8c5b7602d9703217dda", "53e9b2e5b7602d9703d9aa2a", "56d8f377dabfae2eee83cc69", "53e9bd55b7602d97049ec0c9", "53e9a88db7602d97031dd3f6", "53e9b0fbb7602d9703b7762b", "53e99d58b7602d97026134e2", "56e1bf16dabfaecceb4c926b", "53e9a636b7602d9702f67b58", "53e9a539b7602d9702e5e550", "53e9aaa9b7602d9703424723", "55a3d4b5612ca648687a325d", "56d91b2cdabfae2eee7af261", "55a3edfd612ca648687e160a", "55a41731612ca648688593d5", "53e9a089b7602d970297393c", "53e9b12ab7602d9703bad7d0", "53e9b0abb7602d9703b18f20", "53e9b489b7602d9703f9039f", "53e9a5afb7602d9702edca35", "53e9b355b7602d9703e2c905", "53e99c13b7602d97024c2601", "53e9b1c9b7602d9703c5b5aa", "53e99a6db7602d97022de248", "53e9a973b7602d97032ca188", "55a4e893612c6b12aafdc51b", "53e99b63b7602d970240918d", "53e998cdb7602d97021083e1"]}
{"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e153", "title": "New language found.", "authors": [{"name": "Nigel Williams"}], "venue": "Current biology : CB", "year": 2010, "page_start": "R909", "page_end": "R909", "lang": "en", "volume": "20", "issue": "21", "issn": "1879-0445", "doi": "10.1016/j.cub.2010.10.042", "url": ["http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.cub.2010.10.042", "http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21105220?report=xml&format=text"], "abstract": "As human languages are increasingly dying out, the discovery of a new one is striking. Nigel Williams reports."}
{"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e154", "title": "Novel lanthanoid fluoroarsenates", "authors": [{"name": "Karel Lutar"}, {"name": "Horst Borrmann", "org": "Jo\u017eef Stefan Institute, Jamova 39, SI-1000 Ljubljana, Slovenia"}, {"name": "Zoran Mazej", "org": "Jo\u017eef Stefan Institute, Jamova 39, SI-1000 Ljubljana, Slovenia"}, {"name": "Melita Tram\u0161ek", "org": "Jo\u017eef Stefan Institute, Jamova 39, SI-1000 Ljubljana, Slovenia"}, {"name": "Primo\u017e Benki\u010d", "org": "Jo\u017eef Stefan Institute, Jamova 39, SI-1000 Ljubljana, Slovenia"}, {"name": "Boris \u017demva", "org": "Jo\u017eef Stefan Institute, Jamova 39, SI-1000 Ljubljana, Slovenia"}], "venue": "Journal of Fluorine Chemistry", "year": 2000, "keywords": ["ambient temperature", "structures", "three dimensional", "critical temperature", "crystal structure"], "page_start": "155", "page_end": "160", "lang": "en", "volume": "101", "issue": "2", "issn": "Journal of Fluorine Chemistry", "doi": "10.1016/S0022-1139(99)00152-9", "url": ["http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S0022-1139(99)00152-9"], "abstract": "A family of lanthanoid(III) hexafluoroarsenates(V), La (AsF 6 ) 3 , LnF(AsF 6 ) 2 , Ln = Ce\u2013Er, and Ln 2 F 3 (AsF 6 ) 3 , Ln = Tm, Yb, Lu, has been stabilized with some fluoro bases as additional ligands forming new compounds: La(HF) 2 (AsF 6 ) 3 , La(XeF 2 ) 2.5 (AsF 6 ) 3 and Ln(AsF 3 ) 3 (AsF 6 ) 3 , Ln = Ce, Pr. La(HF) 2 (AsF 6 ) 3 was prepared by solvothermal reaction in AsF 5 above its critical temperature, while syntheses of other compounds were carried out in anhydrous hydrogen fluoride (aHF) as a solvent at ambient temperature. When Ln 2 O 3 were used as starting compounds in the AsF 5 /aHF superacid medium the oxonium compounds of the type (H 3 O) x Ln y F z (AsF 6 ) x +3 y \u2212 z were synthesized. The crystal structures of (H 3 O) 8 La 2 F(AsF 6 ) 13 , (H 3 O) 4 La 2 F(AsF 3 ) 2 (AsF 6 ) 9 , La(HF) 2 (AsF 6 ) 3 and La(XeF 2 ) 2.5 (AsF 6 ) 3 exhibit low-dimensional structural features, while the structure of Ln(AsF 3 ) 3 (AsF 6 ) 3 (Ln = Ce, Pr) shows a three-dimensional network. In the structure of La(HF) 2 (AsF 6 ) 3 bonding interaction between HF and a metal centre is described for the first time. Keywords Lanthanoid(III) hexafluoroarsenates(V) Syntheses Structures 1 Introduction Lewis amphoterism is well demonstrated in the lanthanoid trifluoride series. A large number of compounds with LnF 3 (Ln = La\u2013Lu) as fluoro acid and a smaller number of compounds with LnF 3 as fluoro base are described in the literature. Majority of these compounds were prepared by solid state reactions from mixtures of binary fluorides at elevated temperatures. Because of the lanthanoid contraction the effective nuclear charge and therefore the fluoride ion affinity of lanthanoid elements is increasing along the series with LaF 3 being the weakest and LuF 3 the strongest fluoro acid. Ionic radii of lanthanoids in +4 oxidation state are even smaller and consequently LnF 4 type compounds are stronger fluoro acids than corresponding trifluorides. The amphoteric behaviour of LnF 3 is clearly demonstrated in two systems, XeF 6 /LnF 3 [1] and LnF 3 /AuF 3 [2\u20135] . In the first case, LnF 3 acts as Lewis acid and results showed that reactions between XeF 6 and LnF 3 (Ln = La\u2013Tb) do not proceed due to too weak acidity of these trifluorides. DyF 3 is the first enough strong Lewis acid in the series and the compound with composition 3XeF 6 \u00b7DyF 3 was obtained. From dysprosium on the compounds of the type 6XeF 6 \u00b7LnF 3 (Ln = Ho, Er, Tm, Yb, Lu) were isolated. However, with the stronger fluoro acids LnF 4 xenon(VI) fluorolanthanoates(IV) were formed, XeF 6 \u00b72CeF 4 , XeF 6 \u00b74PrF 4 and XeF 6 \u00b72TbF 4 . In the system LnF 3 /AuF 3 lanthanoid trifluorides act as Lewis bases. The stoichiometry of isolated products, Ln(AuF 4 ) 3 (Ln = La), Ln 2 F(AuF 4 ) 5 (Ln = La, Pr, Nd, Sm, Gd, Tb, Dy, Ho, Er) and LnF(AuF 4 ) 2 (Ln = Tm, Yb, Lu) is in accordance with the decreasing fluorobasicity of LnF 3 along the series. Preliminary experiments using aHF as a solvent in the systems LnF 3 /Lewis acids were performed already in 1950s by Clifford [6] . Recently, this synthetic route was successfully applied in the reactions between LnF 3 and some gaseous (AsF 5 [7,8,9] , BF 3 [7,8,10] , GeF 4 [11] ), liquid (SbF 5 [11] ) and solid (BiF 5 [11] ) fluoro acids. In the case of AsF 5 it was shown that in aHF solution Ln(AsF 6 ) 3 composition is stable for all representatives, however, as solids three different types of compounds were isolated at room temperature, La(AsF 6 ) 3 , LnF(AsF 6 ) 2 (Ln = Ce\u2013Er), and Ln 2 F 3 (AsF 6 ) 3 (Ln =Tm, Yb, Lu). Lanthanoid tetrafluorides (CeF 4 , PrF 4 and TbF 4 ) are too weak fluoro bases to form LnF x (AsF 6 ) 4\u2212 x compounds [9] . Though lanthanoid difluorides are stronger Lewis bases than lanthanoid trifluorides it was not possible to isolate lanthanoid(II) hexafluoroarsenates as AsF 5 in aHF readily oxidizes Ln 2+ to Ln 3+ (Ln = Sm) [12] . However, with the non-oxidizing Lewis acid GeF 4 in aHF as a solvent it is possible to synthesize Ln 2+ salts, e.g., SmGeF 6 [13] . All attempts to grow single crystals of compounds LnF x (AsF 6 ) 3\u2212 x with x = 0, 1 and 1.5 [9] failed. However, stabilization of these compounds was achieved by using some fluoro bases (HF, XeF 2 , AsF 3 ) as additional ligands. A similar approach was also successful with OPF 3 or NSF 3 [14] , and non-fluorine ligands, SO 2 [15] and CH 3 CN [16] . In the present contribution syntheses and structures of La(HF) 2 (AsF 6 ) 3 [17] , La(XeF 2 ) 2.5 (AsF 6 ) 3 [18] and Ln(AsF 3 ) 3 (AsF 6 ) 3 , Ln = Ce, Pr [19] are discussed. When lanthanoid(III) fluorides are replaced by corresponding oxides as starting compounds in the AsF 5 /aHF superacid medium, a whole series of new oxonium salts with general formula (H 3 O) x Ln y F z (AsF 6 ) x +3 y \u2212 z was obtained [20] . The structures of (H 3 O) 8 La 2 F(AsF 6 ) 13 and (H 3 O) 4 La 2 F(AsF 3 ) 2 (AsF 6 ) 9 are compared with the above mentioned lanthanoid complexes. 2 Syntheses 2.1 Synthesis of LnF x (AsF 6 ) 3\u2212x [9] LnF 3 are insoluble in aHF, but are readily dissolved in aHF acidified with AsF 5 forming solutions of solvated lanthanoid cations Ln(HF) n 3+ and AsF \u2212 anions: (1) LnF 3 +m AsF 5 \u2192 HF 298 K [ Ln ( HF ) n 3+ ]( AsF 6 \u2212 ) 3 +(m\u22123) AsF 5 m\u22653. On the basis of the similarity of Ln 3+ spectra in the aqueous and aHF solutions it is anticipated that most probably n = 9 for lighter and n =8 for heavier LnF 3+ ions [12] . It was shown through the whole series of lanthanoids that last traces of LnF 3 are dissolved in aHF when exactly the mole ratio Ln : AsF 5 = 1 : 3 is reached. From these solutions the solid compounds of particular lanthanoid metal can be isolated by pumping off volatiles at room temperature: LnF x (AsF 6 ) 3\u2212 x , x = 0 for La, x = 1 for Ce\u2013Er, and x = 1.5 for Tm\u2013Lu. 2.2 Preparation of the crystals of (H 3 O) 8 La 2 F(AsF 6 ) 13 and (H 3 O) 4 La 2 F(AsF 3 ) 2 (AsF 6 ) 9 [20] Reactions of Ln 2 O 3 in superacid medium AsF 5 \u2013aHF proceed according to the reaction: (2) Ln 2 O 3 +m AsF 5 +p HF \u2192 298 K ( H 3 O + ) 3 [ Ln ( HF ) n 3+ ] 2 ( AsF 6 \u2212 ) 9 +(m\u22129) AsF 5 +(p\u22129\u22122n) HF m\u22659 p>300. For these solutions, depending on the reaction conditions and position of the lanthanoid metal in the series, oxonium compounds with general formula (H 3 O) x Ln y F z (AsF 6 ) x +3 y \u2212 z were isolated at room temperature. Colourless crystals of (H 3 O) 8 La 2 F(AsF 6 ) 13 were prepared by solvolysis of the isolated compound (H 3 O) 3 La 2 F(AsF 6 ) 8 in aHF, and subsequent very slow static evaporation of this super-saturated solution. Colourless crystals of (H 3 O) 4 La 2 F(AsF 3 ) 2 (AsF 6 ) 9 were prepared from La 2 O 3 and aHF under solvothermal conditions in AsF 5 above its critical temperature ( T c = 337 K [21] ). Although the reaction was carried out in a teflon-lined nickel vessel, AsF 3 was formed by the reduction of AsF 5 on the metal wall of the outside reaction vessel due to severe reaction conditions. 2.3 Synthesis of La(XeF 2 ) 2.5 (AsF 6 ) 3 [18] First the aHF solution of La(AsF 6 ) 3 with stoichiometric amount of AsF 5 was prepared according to Eq. (1) . Then an excess of XeF 2 was added to this solution: (3) La ( AsF 6 ) 3( solv ) +m XeF 2 \u2192 298 K La ( XeF 2 ) n ( AsF 6 ) 3 +(m\u2212n) XeF 2 \u2192 dynamic vacuum 298 K La ( XeF 2 ) 2.5 ( AsF 6 ) 3 m\u226512. After the reaction was completed the white solid of the composition La(XeF 2 ) 2.5 (AsF 6 ) 3 , determined by mass balance, was obtained by pumping off volatiles at 298 K. The single crystals of La(XeF 2 ) 2.5 (AsF 6 ) 3 were obtained by evaporating solvent from the super-saturated solution of La(XeF 2 ) 2.5 (AsF 6 ) 3 in aHF. 2.4 Synthesis of La(HF) 2 (AsF 6 ) 3 [17] La(HF) 2 (AsF 6 ) 3 was prepared in the form of colourless single crystals by the reaction between stoichiometric amounts of LaF 3 and aHF under solvothermal conditions in AsF 5 above its critical temperature. 2.5 Synthesis of Ln(AsF 3 ) 3 (AsF 6 ) 3 , Ln = Ce, Pr [19] The procedure for the preparation of Ln(AsF 3 ) 3 (AsF 6 ) 3 , Ln = La, Ce, Pr is analogous to the synthesis of La(XeF 2 ) 2.5 (AsF 6 ) 3 . The only difference is that instead of XeF 2 arsenic trifluoride is used as a fluoro base (see Section 2.3 ). It was not possible to prepare single crystals of these compounds from super-saturated aHF solutions. Single crystals of Ce(AsF 3 ) 3 (AsF 6 ) 3 and Pr(AsF 3 ) 3 (AsF 6 ) 3 were prepared by reactions of CeF 3 or PrF 3 and aHF under solvothermal conditions in AsF 5 above its critical temperature. During the reactions some reduction of AsF 5 to AsF 3 occurred (see also Section 2.2 ). 3 Discussion Lanthanoid hexafluoroarsenates represent potential precursors for the preparation of new lanthanoid compounds or already known compounds at milder conditions. The main advantage of performing reactions in solutions is a better control of some reaction conditions, that can influence on some parameters of reaction products, e.g., particle size, homogeneous distribution of possible doping elements, which are crucial for the applicable properties of the synthesized compounds. Structures of all the compounds described above except Ln(AsF 3 ) 3 (AsF 6 ) 3 , Ln = Ce, Pr, are characterized by low-dimensional building blocks. Compounds (H 3 O) 8 La 2 F(AsF 6 ) 13 and (H 3 O) 4 La 2 F(AsF 3 ) 2 (AsF 6 ) 9 have chain structure, compound La(XeF 2 ) 2.5 (AsF 6 ) 3 has a column structure, compound La(HF) 2 (AsF 6 ) 3 forms layers, while compound Ln(AsF 3 ) 3 (AsF 6 ) 3 (Ln = Ce, Pr) exhibits three-dimensional network. The basic unit of the (H 3 O) 8 La 2 F(AsF 6 ) 13 structure is formed by a fluorine atom located at a centre of symmetry and connecting two lanthanum atoms ( Fig. 1 ). This arrangement is bridged by four AsF 6 units. To extend the coordination of each La atom, additional three AsF 6 units are coordinated without further bridging. The environment of the La atom is completed by trans -bridging AsF 6 units leading to a zig\u2013zag chain of alternating La 2 F and AsF 6 units. The final structure is formed by four H 3 O + cations and one discrete AsF 6 \u2212 anion per La atom which are located between the chains. Zig\u2013zag chains are running in the a -axis direction ( Figs. 2 and 3 ). Within the structure La is nine-coordinate, one triangular face of trigonal prism being tilted by about 20\u00b0 due to considerably shorter La\u2013F\u2013(La) distance. The structure of (H 3 O) 4 La 2 F(AsF 3 ) 2 (AsF 6 ) 9 is closely related to the structure of (H 3 O) 8 La 2 F(AsF 6 ) 13 . The main difference is that two AsF 6 units (As*) are replaced by two AsF 3 molecules ( Fig. 1 ). However, here only two H 3 O + cations per La atom are between the chains and also there are no free AsF 6 units between the chains. Lanthanum in La(XeF 2 ) 2.5 (AsF 6 ) 3 structure is nine-coordinate with six fluorine ligands from AsF 6 groups forming a regular trigonal prism, while three XeF 2 molecules (two terminal and one bridging) are capping the rectangular faces of the trigonal prism ( Fig. 4 ). La atom is connected through all six AsF 6 units to neighbouring two La atoms thus forming an infinite [La(AsF 6 ) 3 ] n chain. The structure consists of columns of two such chains running parallel and which are bridged by one XeF 2 molecule per formula unit ( Fig. 5 ). The structure of La(HF) 2 (AsF 6 ) 3 reveals a novel type of bonding interaction as HF molecules are connected directly to the metal centre ( Fig. 6 ). Within the structure lanthanum is 10-coordinate, the polyhedron about the metal centre being a trigonal prism, whose triangular faces are related by a crystallographic mirror plane. The triangular faces are formed by two fluorine ligands provided by AsF 6 units (As2) and one by HF molecules, respectively. Furtheron, these AsF 6 units are cis -bridging to neighbouring La atoms. The three rectangular faces of the prism are capped in a characteristic way by four fluorine ligands provided by three AsF 6 (As1) units, two sharing an apical fluorine and one sharing an edge. All four fluorine atoms capping the prism as well as the connected As atoms are located in the mirror plane. Finally, an infinite network is formed, including the bridging AsF 6 units already mentioned above. The resulting infinite slabs are connected via hydrogen bonding ( Fig. 7 ). Coordination of cerium or praseodymium in Ce(AsF 3 ) 3 (AsF 6 ) 3 or Pr(AsF 3 ) 3 (AsF 6 ) 3 is similar to that of lanthanum in La(XeF 2 ) 2.5 (AsF 6 ) 3 , with exception that all three AsF 3 molecules are terminal ( Fig. 8 ). Six fluorine ligands provided by AsF 6 units form regular trigonal prism while three fluorine ligands provided by AsF 3 molecules are capping rectangular faces of this prism. However, the different connection of AsF 6 units between two Ce (or Pr) atoms, trans -manner in contrast to cis -manner in La(XeF 2 ) 2.5 (AsF 6 ) 3 , results in a three-dimensional network instead of infinite chains ( Fig. 9 ). A view of the packing down the c -axis shows mainly the three-fold symmetry induced by the space group. The Ce (or Pr) atoms together with the bridging AsF 6 units form columns with hexagonal cross-section. The channels formed this way are filled by AsF 3 units ( Fig. 10 ). By the examples mentioned above, it was demonstrated that the directed design of structures is possible by choosing proper ligands. In this way structures such as chains, double-chains or towers, layers and finally three-dimensional networks could be selectively obtained. {"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e166", "title": "Natural language inference.", "authors": [{"name": "Yorick A. Wilks"}], "venue": "Natural language inference.", "year": 1973, "keywords": ["weak inductive knowledge", "non-deductive inference", "possible chain", "natural language inference", "anaphoric inference procedure", "possible referents", "preference semantics system", "english pronoun", "natural language analysis", "available knowledge", "anaphoric inference problem", "natural language", "syntax", "semantics", "computer programming", "computational linguistics", "machine translation", "english language"], "n_citation": 17, "lang": "en", "abstract": "The paper describes the way in which a Preference Semantics system for natural language analysis and generation tackles a difficult class of anaphoric inference problems (finding the correct referent for an English pronoun in context): those requiring either analysis (conceptual) knowledge of a complex sort, or requiring weak inductive knowledge of the course of events in the real world. The method employed converts all available knowledge to a canonical template form and endeavors to create chains of non-deductive inferences from the unknowns to the possible referents. Its method of selecting among possible chains of inferences is consistent with the overall principle of \"semantic preference\" used to set up the original meaning representation, of which these anaphoric inference procedures are a manipulation."}

{"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e16a", "title": "Natural language inference", "authors": [{"name": "Christopher D. Manning", "org": "Stanford University"}, {"name": "Bill Maccartney", "org": "Stanford University"}], "venue": "Natural language inference", "year": 2009, "keywords": ["semantic theory", "semantic exclusion", "semantic containment", "lexical semantic knowledge", "natural language inference", "good alignment", "standard nli evaluation", "natural logic", "semantic structure", "alignment scoring function", "formal deduction"], "n_citation": 9, "lang": "en", "abstract": "Inference has been a central topic in artificial intelligence from the start, but while automatic methods for formal deduction have advanced tremendously, comparatively little progress has been made on the problem of natural language inference (NLI), that is, determining whether a natural language hypothesis h can justifiably be inferred from a natural language premise p. The challenges of NLI are quite different from those encountered in formal deduction: the emphasis is on informal reasoning, lexical semantic knowledge, and variability of linguistic expression. This dissertation explores a range of approaches to NLI, beginning with methods which are robust but approximate, and proceeding to progressively more precise approaches.We first develop a baseline system based on overlap between bags of words. Despite its extreme simplicity, this model achieves surprisingly good results on a standard NLI evaluation, the PASCAL RTE Challenge. However, its effectiveness is limited by its failure to represent semantic structure. To remedy this lack, we next introduce the Stanford RTE system, which uses typed dependency trees as a proxy for semantic structure, and seeks a low-cost alignment between trees for p and h, using a cost model which incorporates both lexical and structural matching costs. This system is typical of a category of approaches to NLI based on approximate graph matching. We argue, however, that such methods work best when the entailment decision is based, not merely on the degree of alignment, but also on global features of the aligned \u2329p, h\u232a pair motivated by semantic theory. Seeking still greater precision, we devote the largest part of the dissertation to developing an approach to NLI based on a model of natural logic. We greatly extend past work in natural logic, which has focused solely on semantic containment and monotonicity, to incorporate both semantic exclusion and implicativity. Our system decomposes an inference problem into a sequence of atomic edits which transforms p into h; predicts a lexical entailment relation for each edit using a statistical classifier; propagates these relations upward through a syntax tree according to semantic properties of intermediate nodes; and composes the resulting entailment relations across the edit sequence. Finally, we address the problem of alignment for NLI, by developing a model of phrase-based alignment inspired by analogous work in machine translation, including an alignment scoring function, inference algorithms for finding good alignments, and training algorithms for choosing feature weights."}

Despite early disease recurrence and/or progression, resection of NLM with or without combined ablation provides long-term survival and symptom improvement. {"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e199", "title": "Neo-Lamarckian medicine.", "authors": [{"name": "Root Gorelick"}], "venue": "Medical hypotheses", "year": 2004, "keywords": ["genotype by environment interaction", "nucleotides", "public health", "free radical", "quantitative genetics", "cell division"], "n_citation": 23, "page_start": "299", "page_end": "303", "lang": "en", "volume": "62", "issue": "2", "issn": "0306-9877", "doi": "10.1016/S0306-9877(03)00329-3", "url": ["http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S0306-9877(03)00329-3", "http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14962644?report=xml&format=text"], "abstract": "Darwinian medicine is the treatment of disease based on evolution. The underlying assumption of Darwinian medicine is that traits are coded by genes, which are often assumed to be sequences of DNA nucleotides. The quantitative genetic ramification of this perspective is that traits, including disease susceptibility, are either caused by genes or by the environment, with genotype-by-environment interactions usually considered statistical artefacts. I emphasize also examining those epigenetic signals that can be altered by environmental perturbations and then transmitted to subsequent generations. Although seldom studied, environmentally-alterable meiotically-heritable epigenetic signals exist and provide a mechanism underlying genotype-by-environment interactions. Environment of a parent can affect its descendants by heritably altering epigenetic signals. Neo-Lamarckian medicine is the application of these evolutionary epigenetic notions to diseases and could have enormous public health and environmental policy implications. If industrial contaminants adversely affect organisms by meiotically-heritably altering their epigenetic signals, then cleaning up these contaminants will not remedy the problem. Once contaminants have adversely altered an individual's epigenetic signals, this harm will be transmitted to future generations even if they are not exposed to the contaminant. Exposure to environmental shocks such as free radicals or other carcinogens can alter cytosine methylation patterns on regulatory genes. This can cause cancer by up-regulating genes for cell division or by down-regulating tumour suppressor genes. Environmentally-alterable meiotically-heritable epigenetic signals could also underlie other diseases, such as diabetes, Prader-Willi syndrome, and many complex diseases. If environmentally-altered meiotically-heritable epigenetic effects are widespread - which is an important open empirical question - they have the potential to alter paradigmatic views of evolutionary medicine and the putative dichotomy of nature versus nurture. The goldstino-induced couplings become important when the (hidden sector) scale of spontaneous supersymmetry breaking, f , is relatively low, of the order of few TeV. In particular, we compute the Higgs potential and show that the (tree level) mass of the lightest Higgs scalar can be increased to the LEP bound for f \u223c 2 \u00a0 TeV to 7 TeV. Moreover, the effective quartic Higgs coupling is increased due to additional tree-level contributions proportional to the ratio of visible to hidden sector supersymmetry breaking scales. This increase can alleviate the amount of fine tuning of the electroweak scale that exists in the MSSM. Among the new goldstino couplings, beyond those in MSSM, the most important ones generate an invisible decay of the Higgs boson into a goldstino and neutralino (if m h > m \u03c7 1 0 ), with a partial decay rate that can be comparable to the SM channel h 0 \u2192 \u03b3 \u03b3 . A similar decay of Z boson is possible if m Z > m \u03c7 1 0 and brings a lower bound on f that must be of about 700 GeV. To externalize this normally covert process, Ss were required to write NLMs to CVC stimuli, then reconstruct the original stimuli from their written NLMs. From data gathered in this way, a model of natural language mediation was constructed: to produce an NLM, S was hypothesized to work sequentially through a stack of transformations (T stack) until some one T succeeded in turning the CVC into a familiar word. The T-stack model was able to predict response measures such as latency and probability of free associations. In further tests of validity, the model successfully predicted: ( a ) learning rate as well as the nature of intrusion errors in paired-associate learning, ( b ) CVC memorability in short-term memory tasks, and ( c ) conventional as well as set-manipulated pronounceability ratings. In the 1990s, the development in laser technology allowed to apply these principles to the light\n microscopy field [6\u20138]. In this context multi-photon excitation (MPE) fluorescence microscopy and second harmonic generation\n (SHG) imaging are representative of the continuing growth of interest in optical microscopy. Although other modern imaging\n techniques like scanning near-field microscopy [9], scanning probe microscopy [10] or electron microscopy [11] provide higher\n spatial resolution, light microscopy techniques have unique characteristics for the three-dimensional (3D) investigation of\n biological structures in hydrated states, including the direct observation of living samples [12\u201314]. Multi-photon microscopy\n relies on the property of fluorescent molecules to simultaneously absorb two or more photons [15]. In this context, the advances\n in fluorescence labelling and the development of new fluorescent/luminescent probes like the so-called quantum dots [16] and\n the visible fluorescent proteins (VFPs), that can be expressed permanently bound to proteins of interest by genetically modified\n cells, allow the study of the complex and delicate relationships existing between structure and function in the four-dimensions\n (x-y-z-t) biological systems domain [17,18]. MPE shares with the confocal microscopy the intrinsical 3D exploration capability and\n provides some additional interesting features. First, MPE greatly reduces photo-interactions and permits to image living samples\n for long time periods. Second, it allows high sensitivity measurements due to the low background signal. Third, since most\n of the fluorescent molecules show a wide two-photon absorption spectrum, MPE allows simultaneous excitation of multiple fluorescent\n molecules with only one excitation wavelength, reducing the effects of chromatic abberations of the optical path. Fourth,\n two-photon microscopy can penetrate into thick and turbid media up to a depth of some 100 \u03bcm. Fifth, MPE can induce chemical\n rearrangement and photochemical reactions within a sub-femtoliter volume in solutions, culture cells and living tissues.\n ", "references": ["53e9a9d9b7602d970333cf0a", "53e99b36b7602d97023d50c0"]}

{"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e1b3", "title": "Naturally light leptoquarks", "authors": [{"name": "Ernest Baver", "org": "Department of Particle Physics"}, {"name": "Miriam Leurer", "org": "Department of Particle Physics"}], "venue": "Physical Review D", "year": 1995, "keywords": ["quarks", "fermions", "coupling", "leptons", "beyond the standard model", "symmetry", "elementary particles"], "page_start": "260", "page_end": "264", "lang": "en", "volume": "51", "issue": "1", "doi": "10.1103/PhysRevD.51.260", "url": ["http://dx.doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevD.51.260"], "abstract": "Light first generation leptoquarks are being hunted for in HERA and at FNAL\nand there are various proposals for further searches in future machines. Such\nleptoquarks are however problematic from a theoretical point of view: Low\nenergy precision measurements imply strong constraints on the couplings of the\nleptoquarks, and up till now the fulfilment of these constraints seemed\nextremely unnatural. Here we show that horizontal symmetries, which are very\nconventional and widely used in the literature for completely different\npurposes, can suppress the unwanted couplings. Therefore light first generation\nleptoquarks can be natural."}

{"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e1b8", "title": "Nutritional labeling legislation", "authors": [{"name": "W. J. de Koe", "org": "Ministry of Public Health, The Netherlands Tel.: +31\u200970\u20093406960; Fax: +31\u200970\u20093405435 e-mail: wjdekoe@bird.nl NL"}], "venue": "Accreditation and Quality Assurance", "year": 1997, "keywords": ["international trade"], "page_start": "56", "page_end": "62", "lang": "en", "volume": "2", "issue": "2", "doi": "10.1007/s007690050099", "url": ["http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s007690050099"], "abstract": "With respect to nutrition labeling, many countries in the world rely on what the Codex Alimentarius Commission (the agency\n responsible for the implementation of the joint FAO/WHO foods standards programme) has accomplished over the past decades\n in this field. The Codex General Standard for the Labeling of Prepackaged Foods is one of the most significant standards developed\n by the Commission and forms the basis for many developments in general with respect to labeling in the world. In order to\n promote a consistent international approach also on nutrition labeling, the Codex adopted almost at the same time in 1985 guidelines on this subject, which were worked out by the committee involved\n in labeling. The driving force for nutrition labeling was actually the view both of consumers and producers that neither improved\n ingredient listing nor a declaration of e.g. macro-nutrients such as fat and protein could replace information on the actual\n nutrient content of a food. In response to consumers' interest in nutrition, producers provided information about the nutrients\n which they considered to be attractive to the consumer. Because producers provided a hotchpotch of nutrient information (including\n claims) on labels, the need for a systematic presentation of this information as \"nutrition labeling\" was triggered. Nutrition\n labeling can be defined as a description intended to inform the consumer of the nutritional properties of a food. The Codex\n guidelines require that the nutrient declaration should appear on the label whenever a nutrition claim is made for a food.\n In accordance with the Codex guidelines, nutrition labeling will enable consumers to follow the dietary guidelines within\n their country. In 1988, a joint FAO/WHO expert consultation on recommended allowances for food labeling purposes, hosted by\n the government of Finland, developed a set of nutrient reference values (NRVs) to serve as the reference standard for the\n Codex guidelines. Although the question whether nutrition labeling should be \"voluntary\" or \"mandatory\" has been under discussion\n for a long time, most countries of the world have opted so far for the voluntary system: the nutrient declaration should appear\n on the label whenever a nutrition claim is made and the labeling should follow the criteria as set out in the Codex guidelines or another set of rules such as those\n of the European Community Council Directive 90/496/EEC on nutrition labeling of foodstuffs. Actions of both Codex Committees\n (the one on food labeling and the one on nutrition and foods for special dietary uses) to come to agreement, especially on\n health claims, could not prevent the United States from going their own regulatory way by enacting in 1990 the Nutrition Labeling\n and Education Act (NLEA) and more recently the Dietary Supplement Health and Education Act (DSH&EA). Both acts actually impede\n international trade. Although both the voluntary and the mandatory systems have their own advantages and disadvantages, the\n overall international nutrition labeling approaches have many similarities. The benefits of the mandatory approach in the\n field of nutrition, consumer education and developments in related fields such as the analytical, must not be underestimated.\n By recently throwing out the health claims temporarily, the food labeling committee agreed at its last meeting to forward\n the draft guidelines for use of nutrition claims to the Codex Commission for adoption at step 8, with the understanding that\n the table of conditions would be considered by the coming session of the committee on nutrition and foods for special dietary\n uses. In Europe, where the subsidiarity principle seems to prevail, it is difficult to forecast whether a worldwide uniform\n system of nutrition labeling can be or will be developed after the Edinburgh (1991) decision by politicians not to embark\n on nutrition labeling in the Community."}

This concern has been expressed both by application users who (rightly) feel inadequately supported by the product software and by developers who are frustrated at not being able to respond to customer requirements. The user wants to be able to interact with a product that works according to his language, culture and conventions. The software developer currently does not have the means or flexibility of providing this support cost-effectively; each application must provide its own resources and be reinvented for each target culture.This paper proposes a solution to this problem -- an architected set of interfaces and resources that will provide consistent, comprehensive, cost-effective support for national language. This solution will provide for migration from, and coexistence with, the current development environment. {"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e1cb", "title": "Normal language acquisition.", "authors": [{"name": "Leslie Rescorla"}, {"name": "Jennifer Mirak"}], "venue": "Seminars in pediatric neurology", "year": 1997, "keywords": ["language acquisition"], "page_start": "70", "page_end": "76", "lang": "en", "volume": "4", "issue": "2", "issn": "1071-9091", "doi": "10.1016/S1071-9091(97)80022-8", "url": ["http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S1071-9091(97)80022-8", "http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9195663?report=xml&format=text"], "abstract": "Long before they start talking, children are skilled at using eye contact, facial expression, and nonverbal gestures to communicate with other people. They also are able to discriminate speech sounds from an early age. Vocabulary learning builds on the child's knowledge about objects, actions, locations, properties, and stages gained as a result of sensorimotor development. Early word combinations allow children to express semantic relationships between these various referents. During the period from 2 to 4 years of age, children move from expressing their ideas in simple telegraphic speech to being able to ask questions, use negation, talk about past and future events, and describe complicated situations using sentences constructed according to complex grammatical rules.", "references": ["56d8f7eddabfae2eee9f9f3f", "56d8e0d4dabfae2eee10c8a9", "53e9af81b7602d97039c49a8", "53e9b9e1b7602d97045dbfda", "53e9b3efb7602d9703eddc5c", "56d82828dabfae2eeeea71e2", "53e9ac95b7602d970366f7c5", "55a54fc624012c2a391b7481", "53e9a515b7602d9702e36fd7", "53e9afeeb7602d9703a40d40", "55a452d42401c6de3b8f7a1b", "56d8dc4cdabfae2eeef4b2f0", "53e9a782b7602d97030bd65f", "53e9ac7bb7602d970364f1f2", "53e9b2dbb7602d9703d8d659", "53e9ba69b7602d97046886af", "53e9a011b7602d97028f17f0", "53e9a618b7602d9702f49bd1", "53e9a57cb7602d9702ea6bc5", "53e9a049b7602d970292fc2b", "53e9a042b7602d970292ab8c", "53e99ea1b7602d970276c28c", "53e9afeeb7602d9703a44cec", "53e99eb4b7602d970277be89", "53e9b0e6b7602d9703b5fad4", "53e9abc9b7602d970357e97a", "53e9b61bb7602d970416f069", "53e99eaeb7602d9702776942", "56d8f7efdabfae2eee9faec8", "53e99a92b7602d970230a534", "56d8282adabfae2eeeea7a44"]}

{"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e1d6", "title": "Negotiating local autonomy", "authors": [{"name": "Robert W. Lake", "org": "Center for Urban Policy Research, Rutgers University, PO Box 489, Piscataway, NJ 08855, USA"}], "venue": "Political Geography", "year": 1994, "n_citation": 78, "page_start": "423", "page_end": "442", "lang": "en", "volume": "13", "issue": "5", "issn": "Political Geography", "doi": "10.1016/0962-6298(94)90049-3", "url": ["http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/0962-6298(94)90049-3"], "abstract": "The political apathy of the late 20th century is being offset by a counter-movement seeking to replace technocratic + political decision making with localized citizen activism. The objective of this movement is to expand the scope of local autonomy, defined here as the capacity of localities to control the social construction of place. Alternative dispute resolution (ADR) techniques, increasingly used in public policy decision making and implementation, offer the normative potential for expanded local empowerment through validation of alternative value structures and modes of discourse. If ADR reduces the salience of rational-technical discourse in public policy making, then adoption of ADR should contribute to local enfranchisement, producing greater local control over the construction of place and augmenting the expression of local autonomy. As evidenced in the case of negotiation with local communities over the siting of hazardous waste facilities, the empowering potential of ADR has been subverted in the process of its implementation by the state. To explain the failure of ADR to empower localities in practice, I identify a series of structural barriers to local autonomy embedded in the state's negotiation process. Contrary to ADR's theoretical inclusivity and normative embrace of parallel discourses, these structural barriers undermine local autonomy by reasserting the dominance of rational-technical discourse in the policy-making process. The state's success in controlling negotiations to maintain pliable communities, however, is short-lived. When understood as a continuing and constitutive relation between the local and the non-local, local autonomy that is blocked by truncated negotiations finds expression through other means.", "references": ["53e99b26b7602d97023c28fa", "53e9b260b7602d9703d0480a", "56d8ea34dabfae2eee4b57b2", "53e9b627b7602d970417ed08", "53e99845b7602d97020734b0", "53e9b2a3b7602d9703d4bb1a", "56d859a4dabfae2eee446b2b", "56d8f679dabfae2eee9682db", "53e9a758b7602d9703091e87", "53e99b26b7602d97023c3492", "53e9b33db7602d9703e11a56", "53e9b6dcb7602d970426d810", "53e9a4c0b7602d9702de0e82", "56d8cc87dabfae2eee80dde8", "56d839dadabfae2eee587169", "56d91b5bdabfae2eee7c2581", "53e9b7fcb7602d97043b0837", "53e9a7b3b7602d97030f3a89", "53e99ad7b7602d9702358b15", "56d8cbaedabfae2eee7a7fe9", "53e9b581b7602d97040c3729", "53e9ab69b7602d9703504b0c", "53e99860b7602d970209c832", "56d8f658dabfae2eee95b61f", "53e9a4aab7602d9702dc871f", "53e9b7e0b7602d970438e0c5", "56d81c04dabfae2eee9aaedb", "53e9b4e9b7602d9704012102"]}

{"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e1f5", "title": "Numerical Linear Algebra", "authors": [{"name": "James E. Gentle", "org": "George Mason University Department of Computational & Data Sciences 4400, University Drive Fairfax VA 220304444 USA"}], "year": 2009, "n_citation": 1, "lang": "en", "doi": "10.1007/978-0-387-98144-4_5", "url": ["http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-0-387-98144-4_5"], "abstract": "More complete coverage of the computational issues in linear algebra are covered in \u010c\u00ed\u017ekov\u00e1 and \u010c\u00ed\u017eek (2004), in Part III\n of Gentle (2007), and in Golub and Van Loan (1996). Computational methods for sparse matrices are discussed in some detail\n in Saad (2003).\n \n Mathematical software for linear algebra has traditionally been some of the best software, from the earlier days when libraries\n in various programming languages were widely distributed to the interpretive systems that allowed direct manipulation of vectors\n and matrices. Currently, there are several relatively mature interactive systems, including Matlab and Octave from an applied\n mathematics heritage, and S-Plus and R that emphasize statistical applications. There continues to be a need for specialized\n software for very large linear systems or for rather specialized applications. There are many libraries for these needs in\n Fortran or C/C++ that are freely available. A list of such software is maintained at \n \n \n \n \n \n The R system is widely used by statisticians. This system provides a wide range of operations for vectors and matrices. It\n treats vectors as special kind of list and matrices as special kinds of rectangular arrays. An impact of this is in writing\n functions that accept matrices; a vector will not be accepted just as a matrix with one dimension being 1. A vector has a\n length attribute but not a dim attribute.\n \n \n "}
{"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e1f6", "title": "Non-lithography Applications", "authors": [{"name": "Marc Madou"}], "year": 2007, "lang": "en", "doi": "10.1007/978-1-4020-5949-0_6", "url": ["http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4020-5949-0_6"], "abstract": "For the WTEC study, the mutually agreed-upon working definition of non-lithography machining included, (1) mechanical (traditional)\n machining and, (2) non-mechanical (non-traditional) machining. In addition to non-lithography-based micromachines, the study\n panelists were also interested in establishing the impact of microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) and nanoelectromechanical\n systems (NEMS) on non-lithography-based machining. Examples include the use of MEMS to make a micromold for plastic micromolding,\n nanoimprint lithography (NIL) and the fabrication of fibers using MEMS spinnerettes.\n \n The panel agreed that lithography-based MEMS and NEMS advances are highly oversold in the most public relations-hungry universities\n and government institutes in the U.S. Although less advertised, nonlithography micromachining, practiced mostly in highly\n competitive, private companies such as Sankyo Seiki, Samsung, and Olympus is most likely to continue to lead to more practical\n products faster. These products include lenses for telephone cameras, flat panel displays, automotive parts, microfuel cells,\n microbatteries, micromotors, and desktop factories (DTFs). Based on the state-of-the-art and current investment levels, both\n private and government, Germany, Switzerland, Japan, and Korea will gain the most from developments in non-lithography-based\n machining, given their long tradition with and heavy investment in this field. The U.S. over the last twenty years has emphasized\n lithography-based MEMS with outstanding research results and a dominant market position, but as many MEMS products have become\n commodity products, Asian countries stand to reap more benefits in the near future from it. Actually, even MEMS foundries,\n which are very hard to make profitable in the U.S., are moving more and more to Asia; Olympus in Japan has already the largest\n MEMS foundry in the world. During our Asia trip we gained, in general, more from our industrial visits than from the visits\n to academic institutions\u2014this is understandable as micromanufacturing is very applied and product-driven, and academia is\n not. We believe that to succeed in nonlithography- based machining a stronger-than-usual link with industrial partners and\n academia is required. In this regard we are now behind in the U.S., although it was in the U.S. that the trend of academia/industry\n collaborations started. The links between industry and academia are now better in both Europe and in Asia. It was speculated\n that technology transfer offices in U.S. academia have become so unwieldy that they prevent smoother and better collaboration\n with industry.\n \n \n \n In some showrooms of the Asian hosts, the panel came to realize that none of the products on display were manufactured in\n the U.S. anymore. As noted in Chapter 4, new product demands are stimulating the invention of new materials and processes.\n The loss of manufacturing goes well beyond the loss of one class of products. If a technical community is dissociated from\n the product needs of the day, say those involved in making larger flat-panel displays or the latest mobile phones, communities\n cannot invent and eventually cannot teach effectively anymore. Chapter 4 lists several such new manufacturing processes. A\n yet more sobering realization is that we might invent new technologies, say in nanofabrication, but not be able to manufacture\n the products that incorporate them. It is nave to say that those new products will still be designed in the U.S. because\n the latest manufacturing processes and newest materials need to be understood and used in order for a good design to be developed.\n \n \n \n To stem the hollowing out of the manufacturing bases within their countries, the governments of many developed countries have\n made huge investments in the miniaturization of new products, including MEMS and NEMS, and in the miniaturization of manufacturing\n tools such as DTFs. These efforts are intended to regain a manufacturing edge. To illustrate this point, Olympus\u2019 Haruo Ogawa\n (the leader of their MEMS team) says that MEMS may help rebuild Japan\u2019s power as a manufacturing nation. Sankyo Seiki believes\n that its DTFs might revive manufacturing in Japan. In Korea the government just started a new DTF project. Finally, in some\n quarters in the U.S., nanotechnology is seen as a means for the U.S. to remain a high-technology innovator. It is difficult\n to predict which of these strategies will enable developed countries to maintain a manufacturing base. But it is clear that\n if any country wants to remain independent\u2014especially in times of war\u2014and maintain a high standard of living, it must remain\n strong in manufacturing. This is especially true if that country is resource-poor. There are several differ ent scenarios\n one can think of to maintain a strong manufacturing edge. One approach is a strategy in which manufacturing of products is\n only transferred abroad if new manufacturing technologies or products of equal or higher value are in the pipeline. The latter\n would require a more guided economy than we are used to in the U.S., but it is a strategy that seems to be paying off very\n well for China now. In another scenario, DTFs will become very automated and require very few human operators, so that exporting\n these machines does not make sense anymore, since no labor costs are saved; this is a free-market approach. Yet another popular\n scenario sees DTFs becoming as popular as desktop publishing; this could be called a socially responsible approach. This has\n been promoted by, for example, MIT\u2019s Neil Gershenfeld, but may be somewhat nave given the current political climate. In this\n scenario manufacturing becomes much less centralized, and many more people get involved. In any of these cases, the impact\n on society would be dramatic.\n \n \n "}

{"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e20a", "title": "Neglected lung cancer.", "authors": [{"name": "Shahar Madjar"}, {"name": "Dov Weissberg"}], "venue": "Lung cancer (Amsterdam, Netherlands)", "year": 1994, "page_start": "105", "page_end": "109", "lang": "en", "volume": "11", "issue": "1-2", "issn": "0169-5002", "doi": "10.1016/0169-5002(94)90287-9", "url": ["http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/0169-5002(94)90287-9", "http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8081700?report=xml&format=text"], "abstract": "Pulmonary nodules of unknown nature may be cancerous and are best treated by early resection. During the past 20 years we have seen 65 patients in whom asymptomatic pulmonary nodules from 5 to 20 mm in diameter were discovered on routine roentgenograms between 1 and 4 years prior to their referral to surgery. These patients have not been investigated for cancer. Instead, they had been 'observed' or treated with antibiotics while their nodules increased in size. At the time of referral, 29 patients had widespread metastases, 28 had locally invasive State III lung cancer, eight had Stage I or Stage II lesions. Only 16 patients had their tumors resected. Sixteen patients (24.6%) survived 1 year or longer; six patients (9.3%) survived more than 2 years. Early resection of all undiagnosed pulmonary nodules is essential. 'Expectant' or antibiotic treatment of these lesions should be condemned. Educational programs for family physicians are urged.", "references": ["55a56352612c6b12ab169be5", "53e9afb4b7602d9703a04c86", "55a56a6424012c2a392297ab", "53e9ac8fb7602d9703666f7a", "53e9aa73b7602d97033e9b00", "55a415be2401c6de3b8169dd", "53e9b061b7602d9703ac5e28"]}

{"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e227", "title": "Neonatal lupus erythematosus.", "authors": [{"name": "Earl D. Silverman"}, {"name": "Dawn Spence"}, {"name": "Robert M. Hamilton"}], "venue": "Pediatric dermatology", "year": 1986, "page_start": "417", "page_end": "424", "lang": "en", "volume": "3", "issue": "5", "issn": "0736-8046", "doi": "10.1016/j.clindermatol.2003.12.019", "url": ["http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.clindermatol.2003.12.019", "http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3809030?report=xml&format=text", "http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S0889-857X(05)70349-5"], "abstract": "Neonatal lupus Erythematosus (NLE) is a disorder characterized by maternal autoantibodies against RNA protein complex, Ro/SSA or SSB/La. These maternal IgG antibodies cross the placenta and potentially lead to fetal tissue damage and the clinical manifestations NLE. NLE is uncommon, affects females more than males, has no race predilection, and involves multiple organs. It has cutaneous manifestations similar to subacute cutaneous lupus erythematosus (SCLE). 1 In addition to skin findings, patients with NLE have a significant risk of congenital heart block (CHB), a potentially fatal complication. Less frequently, hematologic and hepatic abnormalities occur. Approximately half of the reported cases have skin disease and half have CHB. Approximately 10% have both CHB and skin findings. 2 The cutaneous, hematologic, and hepatic abnormalities are transient, clearing by 6 months of age. However, CHB is permanent and requires a pacemaker in many cases. The disorder results from the passive transfer of maternal autoantibodies, anti-RoSSA and anti-La/SSB. Sontheimer and McCauliffe reviewed the pathogenic role of anti-Ro antibody in NLE lesions and summarize evidence supporting its pathogenic role. 3 Additional evidence suggests the possibility that Ro-antigen-specific T-cells may be present in SCLE patients and have the capacity to cause direct injury to the skin. 3 McCuistion and Schoch 4 first suggested this hypothesis in 1954 when they described an infant with LE skin findings born to a mother with systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). Since this initial observation, a number of researchers have documented the role of maternal autoantibodies in the pathogenesis of this disorder. 5\u20137 The true incidence of NLE is not known; however, it is known that NLE accounts for approximately 80% of all cases of CHB, and the incidence of CHB is 1 per 20,000 live births. 8 Therefore, it can be assumed that the incidence of NLE is at {"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e228", "title": "NEONATAL LUPUS ERYTHEMATOSUS", "authors": [{"name": "Earl D. Silverman"}, {"name": "Ronald M. Laxer"}], "venue": "Rheumatic Disease Clinics of North America", "year": 1997, "page_start": "599", "page_end": "618", "lang": "en", "volume": "23", "issue": "3", "issn": "Rheumatic Disease Clinics of North America", "doi": "10.1016/S0889-857X(05)70349-5", "abstract": "Neonatal lupus erythematosus (NLE) is a disease of the newborn defined by the presence of maternal autoantibodies and characteristic clinical features in the neonatal period. Although the autoantibodies often are not associated with clinical disease in the mother, NLE is likely the result of fetal or neonatal tissue damage caused by maternally transmitted IgG autoantibodies. The major clinical manifestations are cardiac, dermatologic, and hepatic. 52,77,86,96 Rarely, hemolytic anemia and thrombocytopenia may occur in addition to a variety of less common features. 67,96 The major morbidity and mortality of NLE results from complete congenital heart block (CCHB). Although the first case recognized as NLE was reported just over 40 years ago, review of the literature reveals a description of this entity almost 70 years ago with the report of two children with CCHB born to a mother with Mikulicz's syndrome (currently recognized as Sj\u00f6gren's syndrome). The NLE syndrome is currently recognized as a disease of the newborn whose clinical features predominantly involve the skin and conducting system of the heart. A variety of less common features also contribute to this syndrome. Over the last 2 decades, NLE syndrome has attracted the interest of clinicians (including rheumatologists, dermatologists, cardiologists, hepatologists, hematologists, neonatologists, and obstetricians) and basic scientists interested in autoantibodies and the development of autoimmune responses. It is an area ripe for investigators studying autoimmune disease, predictors of development of disease manifestations in individuals with autoantibodies, and scientists interested in the development of the cardiac conducting system. Although much has been described, there is still a great deal to be learned. This review of NLE focuses on the clinical manifestations, therapeutic approach, long-term follow-up, and role of autoantibodies."}

To determine the magnitude of nonalcoholic liver disease in patients with heavy alcohol consumption, the data on 145 consecutive patients judged to consume at least 80 g of alcohol daily for prolonged periods, and who underwent liver biopsy at the University of Chicago, were reviewed. Nonalcoholic liver disease was suspected clinically and confirmed by liver biopsy in 40 (28 per cent), whereas alcoholic liver disease was suspected in 105 but confirmed in only 83 (80 per cent). The remaining 22 patients had liver disorders, including cholangitis or pericholangitis, acute hepatitis or some form of chronic hepatitis, for which they required appropriate therapy. Neither clinical features, hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg), anti-HBsAg nor serum glutamic oxaloacetic transaminase to serum glutamic pyruvic transaminase (SGOT:SGPT) ratios distinguished these 22 patients from those with alcoholic liver disease. {"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e243", "title": "Nosocomial Legionnaires' disease", "authors": [{"name": "John W. Kugler"}, {"name": "Jam\u00e9s O. Armitage"}, {"name": "Charles M. Gilchrist"}], "venue": "The American Journal of Medicine", "year": 1983, "page_start": "281", "page_end": "288", "lang": "en", "volume": "74", "issue": "2", "issn": "The American Journal of Medicine", "doi": "10.1016/0002-9343(83)90629-0", "url": ["http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/0002-9343(83)90629-0"], "abstract": "Nosocomial pneumonia caused by Legionella pneumophila serogroup 1 occurred in five patients after bone marrow transplantation for hematologic malignancies. Two patients died as a result of the infection despite treatment with erythromycin. Serologic screening revealed no other cases of Legionnaires' disease in 40 consecutive recipients of bone marrow transplants, giving a frequency of infection of 13 percent. These five cases represent 23 percent of the pneumonia occurring in this group of patients. Patients undergoing bone marrow transplantation are highly susceptible to infectious complications. Legionnaires' disease must now be added to the list of pathogens infecting this group of patients. Erythromycin is not generally a part of standard empiric antibiotic regimens in febrile neutropenic patients, but appears to be a reasonable addition when pneumonia does not respond to conventional, empiric treatment. Even with appropriate therapy, Legionnaires' disease remains a highly lethal infection in immunocompromised hosts."}
{"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e244", "title": "Neonatal lung disease", "authors": [{"name": "William G. Cvetnic"}, {"name": "Jack H. Exogenous surfactant can now be administered for the treatment of respiratory distress syndrome. There are currently a number of surfactants available for clinical use, all of which acutely decrease oxygen and ventilation requirements. Further work, however, is needed to determine the optimal dosage, timing and method of administration as well as the subsequent ventilatory care of these infants. Means of ventilation other than conventional positive pressure have been developed that expand the possibilities of treating the difficult-to-ventilate neonate. These methods include continuous negative pressure, high frequency and synchronized intermittent mechanical ventilation. The important continued role of continuous positive airway pressure must be kept in mind, however, for those infants with respiratory distress syndrome and other diseases which manifest with decreased lung volume and hypoxaemia. Because there are now more survivors in the extremely low birthweight infant categories, there will be an expanding population of infants with various degrees of chronic lung injury secondary to oxygen toxicity as well as barotrauma. The goal of treatment is to limit this lung damage. At times this may be accomplished with the use of corticosteroids. The use of antioxidants and enzyme systems that scavenge toxic oxygen radicals is under investigation. Problems still exist in the management of the larger infant with pulmonary artery hypertension. Many of these infants who fail conventional positive pressure ventilation can be rescued with continuous negative pressure prior to being placed on extracorporeal membrane oxygenation. Investigation also continues in the development of selective pulmonary vasodilator drugs that may be used clinically to lower pulmonary vascular resistance, increase pulmonary blood flow and abate the persistent, severe hypoxaemia that is associated with this problem. Despite advancements in knowledge and technology, it may be difficult to prevent abnormal outcomes. {"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e246", "title": "Non local demosaicing", "authors": [{"name": "Antoni Buades"}, {"name": "Bartomeu Coll"}, {"name": "Jean-Michel Morel"}, {"name": "Catalina Sbert"}], "n_citation": 22, "lang": "en", "abstract": "Demosaicing is the process by which from a single CCD sensor measuring only one color component per pixel, red, green or blue, one can infer a fully color information at each pixel. This inference involves a deep understanding of the interaction between colors and the involvement of local geometry. Although quite successful in making such inferences with very small relative error, state of the art demosaicing methods fail when the local geometry cannot been inferred from the neighboring pixels. In such a case, which occurs (e.g.) when thin structures of fine periodic patterns were present in the original, state of the art methods can create disturbing artifacts, known as zipper eect, blur, and color spots. The aim of this paper is to show that by taking into account the more non-local image geometry, these artifacts can be avoided and an almost satisfactory solution found even in the most critical cases. Since the evaluation of artifacts and their removal is problematic, this paper will introduce three new quality assessment principles which can be measured accurately and consistently. One, the \"grey to grey\" principle, leads to measure how much false color has been added by demosaicing, in particular the zipper eects. The other two criteria, \"noise to noise\" and \"method noise\", have been already introduced for denoising purposes. The first one measures how well demosaicing manages not to create structure from a non structured datum while the second one evaluates the loss of details, texture and geometry.", "references": ["53e99c60b7602d97025102b4", "53e9ba0bb7602d970460d583", "53e9b2ccb7602d9703d7b751", "53e9a447b7602d9702d62e10", "53e9a1c3b7602d9702ab87cd", "53e9a1f3b7602d9702af77d9", "53e9aca7b7602d970368277d", "53e9a501b7602d9702e2135e", "53e9a351b7602d9702c5b198", "53e9aafab7602d970347bf46", "53e99aa5b7602d970231b7b1", "53e9a6d0b7602d9703006870", "53e99b10b7602d970239fcd8", "53e9a6b4b7602d9702fe73a2", "53e9ab64b7602d97034fe3c4", "53e99d6cb7602d9702627beb", "53e9a6b5b7602d9702fe78da", "53e9ade2b7602d97037ec9b0", "53e9b828b7602d97043e05d6", "53e997aab7602d9701f80506", "53e9ababb7602d970355bbc8", "53e9a45cb7602d9702d79adb", "53e99aa5b7602d970231b7af"]}

Clarke", "org": "Southern Illinois University, Carbondale, USA"}], "lang": "en", "doi": "10.1007/978-94-010-0011-6_6", "abstract": "\n A natural language is a language spoken and understood by all normal adult members of a speech community. It stands in contrast to specialized languages, both spoken and written, used within sub-groups of this community to perform specialized tasks, though shared in varying\n degrees with members outside these sub-groups. Both natural and specialized languages have lexical items whose meaning is\n specified within the semantic fields just discussed. In addition, they have the resources for combining sentences into blocks of discourse as sequences of sentences about some common topic or related topics. A discourse block can vary in length from a short conversational\n exchange or haiku poem to a novel or many-volume history of a nation. For discourse formation we resort to the use of linking\n words to form from sentences a variety of types of combinations.\n \n "}

{"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e270", "title": "Nonlinear ligament viscoelasticity.", "authors": [{"name": "Paolo Provenzano"}, {"name": "Roderic Lakes"}, {"name": "Thomas Keenan"}, {"name": "Ray Vanderby, Jr."}], "venue": "Annals of biomedical engineering", "year": 2001, "keywords": ["quasilinear viscoelasticity ~qlv!.", "ligament", "creep", "\u2014 stress relaxation", "stress relaxation", "biomedical engineering"], "n_citation": 31, "page_start": "908", "page_end": "914", "lang": "en", "volume": "29", "issue": "10", "issn": "0090-6964", "doi": "10.1114/1.1408926", "url": ["http://dx.doi.org/10.1114/1.1408926", "http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11764321?report=xml&format=text"], "abstract": "Ligaments display time-dependent behavior, characteristic of a viscoelastic solid, and are nonlinear in their stress-strain response. Recent experiments (25) reveal that stress relaxation proceeds more rapidly than creep in medial collateral ligaments, a fact not explained by linear viscoelastic theory but shown by Lakes and Vanderby (17) to be consistent with nonlinear theory. This study tests the following hypothesis: nonlinear viscoelasticity of ligament requires a description more general than the separable quasilinear viscoelasticity (QLV) formulation commonly used. The experimental test for this hypothesis involves performing both creep and relaxation studies at various loads and deformations below the damage threshold. Freshly harvested, rat medial collateral ligaments (MCLs) were used as a model. Results consistently show a nonlinear behavior in which the rate of creep is dependent upon stress level and the rate of relaxation is dependent upon strain level. Furthermore, relaxation proceeds faster than creep; consistent with the experimental observations of Thornton et al. (25) The above results from rat MCLs are not consistent with a separable QLV theory. Inclusion of these nonlinearities would require a more general formulation.", "references": ["53e9a525b7602d9702e4728f", "53e9adffb7602d970380a69d", "53e9a2f3b7602d9702bfcdad", "53e9ba39b7602d9704648333", "53e9adb6b7602d97037b9e5d", "53e9bd04b7602d970498eecf", "53e9accbb7602d97036a9b6e", "53e9ba95b7602d97046be3ed", "53e9a66eb7602d9702f9f6d8", "53e9a789b7602d97030c2fa5", "53e9b10fb7602d9703b8cac4", "53e99924b7602d9702161ece", "53e9a089b7602d9702972a58", "53e9b275b7602d9703d1914c", "53e99d44b7602d97025fa8ae", "53e9a3fbb7602d9702d16984", "53e9bb23b7602d970475d4f4"]}

The patients were hospitalized for 3 to 5 days after procedure. {"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e28a", "title": "Separation of a binary fluid mixture in a porous horizontal cavity.", "authors": [{"name": "Bilal Elhajjar"}, {"name": "Marie-Catherine Charrier-Mojtabi"}, {"name": "Abdelkader Mojtabi"}], "venue": "Physical review. E, Statistical, nonlinear, and soft matter physics", "year": 2008, "n_citation": 35, "page_start": "026310", "page_end": "026310", "lang": "en", "volume": "77", "issue": "2 Pt 2", "issn": "1539-3755", "doi": "10.1103/PhysRevE.77.026310", "url": ["http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18352125?report=xml&format=text"], "abstract": "Thermogravitational separation has, until now, been used in differentially heated vertical cells, called thermogravitational columns (TGCs). The cell can be either a slit or an annular cavity whose two isothermal faces are maintained at different temperatures T1 and T2. In this study, we show contrary to what has been done until now, that it is possible to carry out the separation of the species of a binary mixture in the classical configuration of Rayleigh-B\u00e9nard (horizontal cell heated from below with the separation ratio psi>psi(mono)>0 or from above with psi<0); we obtain a monocellular flow for psi>psi(mono) at the onset of convection. The species separation, in a horizontal cell, is obtained without fear of the remixing observed in vertical thermogravitational cells for fluids with negative Soret coefficients. In this situation, the heaviest component concentrates in the upper part of the cell creating an unstable physical situation. We improve the efficiency of separation for the development of an industrial process of separation. We study the thermogravitational separation of the components of a binary fluid mixture saturating a horizontal porous layer, in the presence of the Soret effect. The horizontal walls of the cavity are impermeable and maintained at constant and different temperatures. The system of equations governing the problem has an equilibrium solution with a vertical stratification of temperature and concentration. This solution loses its stability via a stationary bifurcation for values of the separation ratio psi>psi(0) while, for psi<psi(0), stability is lost via a Hopf bifurcation. For a cavity heated from below, the flow resulting from the stationary bifurcation becomes monocellular beyond a certain value of psi>psi(mono)>0 and leads to a separation of the species between the two ends of the cell. We propose to determine whether the monocellular flow remains stable until the optimum of separation and if we can obtain high separation in the case of a horizontal cavity. We verify that the critical Rayleigh number Ra(c2), associated with the transition between monocellular flow and multicellular flow, is higher than the optimum Rayleigh number leading to maximum separation of species. Thus this study reveals that it is possible to obtain optimal separation before the monocellular flow loses its stability. We show also that the separation inside the horizontal cell in a Rayleigh-B\u00e9nard configuration permits us to produce the same degree of separation but with a greater quantity of each species compared to a thermogravitational vertical column."}

{"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e300", "title": "Negation, Linguistics of", "authors": [{"name": "johan van der auwera"}, {"name": "denies du mon"}], "venue": "International Encyclopedia of Social & Behavioral Sciences", "year": 2001, "keywords": ["polarity", "negation", "focus", "scope", "presupposition", "double negation", "grammaticalization"], "lang": "en", "issn": "International Encyclopedia of Social & Behavioral Sciences", "doi": "10.1016/B0-08-043076-7/02965-X", "url": ["http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/B0-08-043076-7/02965-X"], "abstract": "Negation can be described in terms of a speaker denying or contradicting something. The proposition that is denied is said to be in the \u2018scope\u2019 of the negation, the part of the proposition that is at issue can be called the \u2018focus\u2019 of the negation. The contrary negation of, e.g., \u2018happy\u2019 is \u2018unhappy,\u2019 whereas the contradictory negation is \u2018not happy,\u2019 which allows a state that is in between happiness and unhappiness. The negation is \u2018syntactic\u2019 when the marker is a separate word, a negative verb or a particle (adverb), and the position of the marker is commonly described in terms of its placement vis-\u00e0-vis the verb. The negation is \u2018morphological\u2019 when the marker is an affix. One peculiar form of morphological negation is the \u2018zero morpheme,\u2019 i.e., the absence of an otherwise expected morpheme. The expression of negation is related to the expression of many other categories. One aspect of this relatedness is referred to with the notions of positive or negative \u2018polarity,\u2019 the preference of words and constructions for positive or negative environments.", "references": ["53e99aecb7602d9702375894", "53e99dccb7602d97026908b0", "53e9a6b5b7602d9702fe77c2", "53e9a495b7602d9702db41ad", "56d8f7e9dabfae2eee9f839f", "56d8438adabfae2eee9bbe16", "56d85837dabfae2eee39f3bb", "56d89117dabfae2eeee88f8a", "53e99ae6b7602d970236e318", "53e9afdab7602d9703a2cf73", "53e99b4ab7602d97023eb006", "53e99ae1b7602d9702366851", "53e99dccb7602d970268f5ed", "56d87429dabfae2eee0b9903", "56d87c40dabfae2eee43dd29", "56d898f3dabfae2eee26cdb9"]}
{"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e301", "title": "NON-LEARNING ORGANIZATIONS", "authors": [{"name": "K. BRUNSSON", "org": "The Parliamentary Auditors, 100 12 Stockholm, Sweden"}], "venue": "Scandinavian Journal of Management", "year": 1998, "keywords": ["learning", "unlearning", "procedure", "organizational learning", "learning organization", "organization theory"], "page_start": "421", "page_end": "432", "lang": "en", "volume": "14", "issue": "4", "issn": "Scandinavian Journal of Management", "doi": "10.1016/S0956-5221(98)00002-5", "url": ["http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S0956-5221(98)00002-5"], "abstract": "Whereas organizational learning and unlearning enjoy a well-established reputation in organization theory, non-learning has rarely if ever been discussed. In this article organizational non-learning is characterized, and techniques for non-learning are identified. It is argued that nonlearning organizations have developed a proficiency in ignoring. They may ignore problems and solutions to problems, as well as their own attitudes to these problems and solutions. Non-learning organizations accomplish this essentially by placing problems and potentially problematic issues with somebody else, to be attended to in the future. Their behavior is supported and reinforced by procedures: by the particular distribution of responsibility that procedures entail, and by the fact that procedures recur. A non-learning option allows for organizational discretion. Organizations are free to account for their work in a contradictory manner \u2014 realistic and idealistic at the same time. They are free to learn slowly and to take advantage of their learning."}

{"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e312", "title": "Nominal logic programming", "authors": [{"name": "Greg Morrisett"}, {"name": "James Robert Cheney"}], "venue": "Nominal logic programming", "year": 2004, "keywords": ["nominal logic", "nominal logic program", "logic programming", "nominal logic programming", "application-by-application basis", "programming language", "open term", "programming task", "nominal logic programming language", "nominal constraint problem"], "n_citation": 13, "lang": "en", "abstract": "Names, name-binding, and equivalence of expressions up to \u201csafe\u201d renaming of bound names are often encountered in programming tasks, especially in writing programs that manipulate symbolic data such as mathematical expressions or other programs. Most programming languages provide no support for programming with names and binding, so operations like renaming and substitution must be written by hand, on an application-by-application basis. been developed by Gabbay and Pitts, based on defining concepts like name-binding and substitution in terms of more primitive concepts including name-swapping and freshness. We call this approach nominal This dissertation investigates nominal logic programming, or logic programming using nominal logic. The contributions of this dissertation are as follows. A nominal logic programming language called \u03b1Prolog is presented, along with examples of programs that are particularly convenient to write in \u03b1Prolog. A revised form of nominal logic that provides a suitable foundation for nominal logic programming is developed. Both operational and denotational semantics for nominal logic programming are given, and soundness and completeness properties are proved. The unification and other nominal constraint problems that must be solved during execution of nominal logic programs are identified, and the complexity of and algorithms for solving these constraints are investigated. techniques for programming with names and binding, notably higher-order is both simpler and more expressive than HOAS: in particular, HOAS cannot easily handle open terms, or terms with an unknown number is no problem with open terms. These contributions support the contention that nominal logic programming is a powerful technique for programming with names and binding."}

The work reported here was carried out by the authors at CRL, NMSU under collaboration with both the Department of Defense and Cycorp, Inc. The primary motivation of this relatively small-scale exercise was to arrive at an independent assessment of the utility of Cyc's knowledge and inference capabilities for solving difficult problems in NLP and machine translation. Word sense disambiguation and coreference resolution were chosen as the two problems for this study. We conclude from this exercise that Cyc in fact has a large amount of knowledge that is potentially useful for solving these problems in NLP. However, the knowledge in Cyc is not directly applicable to the problems either in an exclusively Cyc-based solution or one where Cyc is used to improve the performance of other methods. In this report, we have attempted to identify the primary reasons why Cyc cannot readily solve NLP problems, to illustrate our findings with many real-world examples, and to suggest changes or However, almost none of the commercial parallel database systems use hashing-based join algorithms, using instead nested-loops with index or sort-merge. While the research literature abounds with comparisons between the various hash-based and sort-merge join algorithms, to our knowledge there is no published comparison between the parallel hash-based algorithms and a parallel nested loops algorithm with index. In this paper we present a comparison of four variants of parallel index nested loops algorthims with the parallel hybrid hash algorithm. The conclusions of our experiments both with an analytic model and with an implementation in the Gamma parallel database system are that (1) overall, parallel hybrid hash is the method of choice, but (2) htere are caess where nested-loops with index wins big enough that systems could profit from implementing both algorithms. {"id": "53e99837b7602d970205e350", "title": "Non-LTE Revisited", "authors": [{"name": "N. PRZYBILLA", "org": "Institute for Astronomy|University of Hawaii|Institut f\u00fcr Astronomie und Astrophysik"}, {"name": "K. BUTLER", "org": "Institute for Astronomy|University of Hawaii|Institut f\u00fcr Astronomie und Astrophysik"}, {"name": "S. R. BECKER", "org": "Institute for Astronomy|University of Hawaii|Institut f\u00fcr Astronomie und Astrophysik"}, {"name": "R. P. KUDRITZKI", "org": "Institute for Astronomy|University of Hawaii|Institut f\u00fcr Astronomie und Astrophysik"}], "year": 2004, "keywords": ["iron", "quantum mechanics"], "lang": "en", "abstract": "The development of sophisticated techniques for quantum-mechanical computations has lead to the determination of large amounts of accurate atomic data by e.g. the Opacity and IRON Projects in recent years, stimulated by the demands of astrophysical and fusion research. Here, we report on the incorporation of such data in a new generation of non-LTE model atoms for a number of elements of astrophysical relevance. First applications are presented, indicating that significant improvement can be achieved in stellar parameter and elemental abundance studies when the ubiquitous non-LTE effects are addressed thoroughly with accurate atomic data. At best, stellar effective temperatures can be constrained to better than 1% and surface gravities to 0.05-0.10 dex. A high degree of redundancy is obtained by exploiting multiple independent indicators (ionization equilibria, Stark-broadened hydrogen lines). The uncertainties in abundance determinations can be reduced to typically 0.05- 0.10 dex (random) and 0.07-0.12 dex (systematic 1 -errors), even in supergiants. The new results demonstrate that even classical problems like the line formation for hydrogen still offer surprises, and they caution us not to trust apparently well-established assumptions.", "references": ["53e99a7fb7602d97022f1f4c"]}
